In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims April 2016 as National Cancer Control Month. He highlights the progress made in cancer research, but acknowledges that there is still work to be done. The article emphasizes the importance of reducing risk factors for cancer, such as limiting alcohol consumption, controlling sun exposure, exercising, and maintaining a healthy diet. Smoking is identified as a leading cause of cancer, and resources for quitting smoking are provided. The President also mentions the creation of the White House Cancer Moonshot Task Force, which aims to accelerate progress in cancer prevention, treatment, and cures. The Affordable Care Act and the Precision Medicine Initiative are highlighted as efforts to help those with cancer and at risk for cancer. The article calls for renewed efforts to save lives and prevent heartbreak by working towards a future without cancer.